# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crokinole
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crokinole/aerobic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships** are the World Championships for aerobic gymnastics.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] American snooker has a simplified rule set compared to the international game, and is usually played on smaller tables.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Depending upon equipment availability, the balls and *pockets* may be larger than those for standard snooker, up to the size of pool balls and pockets.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] The United States Snooker Association is not connected with the game of American snooker, being the IBSF-recognized US governing body of standard-rules snooker.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] American snooker made its first known in-print appearance in the 1925 edition of Brunswick–Balke–Collender Co.'s *Rules Governing the Royal Game of Billiards*, a rulebook given away by the company (with illustrations of their tables) as a promotional item.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] The previous edition, published in 1914, included snooker, but it was a summary of the original British version, as defined then by the Billiard Association of Great Britain and Ireland, whom the Brunswick booklet credited.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] The 1925 American version had a longer ruleset, opposite the situation today.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Since at least as early as 1946, the Billiard Association of America (BAA), later the Billiard Congress of America (BCA), has published rules for American snooker in every edition of its near-annual rule book.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] The BCA describes the game as "a cousin of snooker as it is played broadly around the world, the regulations giving it a distinctive direction toward the configuration of many American pocket billiard games".
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] American snooker often uses 54 mm (2+1⁄8 inch) balls, but may use standard 52.5 mm (approx.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] It is typically played on a 10 by 5 ft (3.0 by 1.5 m) table (and in private homes, often on even smaller tables), as full-size regulation 12 by 6 ft (3.7 by 1.8 m) British-style tables are rare in the United States, although they are legal for American snooker.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Most serious players obtain proper snooker cues, though novices may settle for a thicker-tipped pool cue.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] American snooker sets often come with *color balls* that are numbered with their *point* values.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] While American snooker shares many similarities to that of the modern international game of snooker, it has some differences.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Foul shots are always awarded as a 7-point foul, as opposed to 4–7 depending on circumstances in the traditional game.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Fouling can also occur if the cue makes contact with the table cloth, causing a 14-point foul.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] Colored balls must be pocketed cleanly, meaning that once the cue ball has struck them, they cannot make contact with any other ball before being pocketed, or it is a foul.
[src:crokinole/american-snooker] As is more traditional with pool games, a *lag* is used in place of a coin flip at the beginning of the match, and also in the case of a *respotted* black.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The **Amish** (/ˈɑːmɪʃ/ ⓘ, also /ˈæmɪʃ/ or /ˈeɪmɪʃ/; Pennsylvania German: *Amisch*), formally the **Old Order Amish**, are a group of traditionalist Anabaptist Christian church fellowships with Swiss and Alsatian origins.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because they maintain a degree of separation from surrounding populations, and hold their faith in common, the Amish have been described by certain scholars as an ethnoreligious group, combining features of an ethnicity and a Christian denomination.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are closely related to Old Order Mennonites and Conservative Mennonites, denominations that are also a part of Anabaptist Christianity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are known for simple living, plain dress, Christian pacifism, and slowness to adopt many conveniences of modern technology, with a view neither to interrupt family time, nor replace face-to-face conversations whenever possible, and a view to maintain self-sufficiency.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish value rural life, manual labor, humility and *Gelassenheit* (submission to God's will).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish church began with a schism in Switzerland within a group of Swiss and Alsatian Mennonite Anabaptists in 1693 led by Jakob Ammann.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Those who followed Ammann became known as Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the second half of the 19th century, the Amish divided into Old Order Amish and Amish Mennonites; the latter do not abstain from using motor cars, whereas the Old Order Amish retained much of their traditional culture.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] When people refer to the Amish today, they normally refer to the Old Order Amish, though there are other subgroups of Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish fall into three main subgroups—the Old Order Amish, the New Order Amish, and the Beachy Amish—all of whom wear plain dress and live their life according to the Bible as codified in their church's *Ordnung*.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish and New Order Amish conduct their worship in German, speak Pennsylvania Dutch, and use buggies for transportation, in contrast to the Beachy Amish who use modern technology (inclusive of motor cars) and conduct worship in the local language of the area in which they reside.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Both the New Order Amish and the Beachy Amish emphasize the New Birth, evangelize to seek converts, and have Sunday schools.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the early 18th century, many Amish and Mennonites emigrated to Pennsylvania for a variety of reasons.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most Old Order Amish, New Order Amish and the Old Beachy Amish speak Pennsylvania Dutch, but Indiana's Swiss Amish also speak Alemannic dialects.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] As of 2024, the Amish population surpassed the 400,000 milestone, with about 405,000 Old Order Amish living in the United States, and over 6,000 in Canada: a population that is rapidly growing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish church groups seek to maintain a degree of separation from the non-Amish world.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Non-Amish people are generally referred to as "English" by the Amish, and outside influences are often described as "worldly".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish church membership begins with adult baptism, usually between the ages of 16 and 23.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Church districts have between 20 and 40 families, and Old Order Amish and New Order Amish worship services are held every other Sunday in a member's home or barn, while the Beachy Amish worship every Sunday in churches.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The rules of the church, the *Ordnung*, which differs to some extent between different districts, are reviewed twice a year by all members of the church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The *Ordnung* must be observed by every member and covers many aspects of Old Order Amish day-to-day living, including prohibitions or limitations on the use of power-line electricity, telephones, and automobiles, as well as regulations on clothing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Generally, a heavy emphasis is placed on church and family relationships.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish typically operate their own one-room schools and discontinue formal education after grade eight (age 13–14).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most Amish do not buy commercial insurance or participate in Social Security.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] As present-day Anabaptists, Amish church members practice nonresistance and will not perform any type of military service.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Anabaptist movement, from which the Amish later emerged, started in circles around Huldrych Zwingli (1484–1531) who led the early Reformation in Switzerland.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In Zürich on January 21, 1525, Conrad Grebel and George Blaurock practiced believer's baptism to each other and then to others.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] This Swiss movement, part of the Radical Reformation, later became known as Swiss Brethren.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The term Amish was first used as a *Schandename* (a term of disgrace) in 1710 by opponents of Jakob Amman, an Anabaptist leader.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The first informal division between Swiss Brethren was recorded in the 17th century between *Oberländers* (those living in the Bernese Oberland) and *Emmentalers* (those living in the Emmental).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The *Oberländers* were a more extreme congregation; their zeal pushed them into more remote areas.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Swiss Anabaptism developed, from this point, in two parallel streams, most clearly marked by disagreement over the preferred treatment of "fallen" believers.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Emmentalers (sometimes referred to as Reistians, after bishop Hans Reist, a leader among the Emmentalers) argued that fallen believers should only be withheld from communion, and not regular meals.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish argued that those who had been banned should be avoided even in common meals.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Reistian side eventually formed the basis of the Swiss Mennonite Conference.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because of this common heritage, Amish and conservative Mennonites from southern Germany and Switzerland retain many similarities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Those who leave the Amish fold tend to join various congregations of Conservative Mennonites.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish began migrating to Pennsylvania, then regarded favorably for its lack of religious persecution and attractive land offers, in the early 18th century as part of a larger migration from the Palatinate and neighboring areas.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Between 1717 and 1750, approximately 500 Amish migrated to North America, mainly to the region that became Berks County, Pennsylvania, but later moved, motivated by land issues and by security concerns tied to the French and Indian War.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Many eventually settled in Lancaster County.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] A second wave of around 1,500 arrived around the mid-19th century and settled mostly in Ohio, Illinois, Iowa, and southern Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most of these late immigrants eventually did not join the Old Order Amish but more liberal groups.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most Amish communities that were established in North America did not ultimately retain their Amish identity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The major division that resulted in the loss of identity of many Amish congregations occurred in the third quarter of the 19th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The forming of factions worked its way out at different times at different places.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The process was rather a "sorting out" than a split.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish people are free to join another Amish congregation at another place that fits them best.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the years after 1850, tensions rose within individual Amish congregations and between different Amish congregations.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Between 1862 and 1878, yearly *Dienerversammlungen* (ministerial conferences) were held at different places, concerning how the Amish should deal with the tensions caused by the pressures of modern society.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The meetings themselves were a progressive idea; for bishops to assemble to discuss uniformity was an unprecedented notion in the Amish church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] By the first several meetings, the more traditionally minded bishops agreed to boycott the conferences.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The more progressive members, comprising roughly two-thirds of the group, became known by the name Amish Mennonite, and eventually united with the Mennonite Church, and other Mennonite denominations, mostly in the early 20th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The more traditionally minded groups became known as the Old Order Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Egli Amish had already started to withdraw from the Amish church in 1858.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They soon drifted away from the old ways and changed their name to "Defenseless Mennonite" in 1908.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because no division occurred in Europe, the Amish congregations remaining there took the same way as the change-minded Amish Mennonites in North America and slowly merged with the Mennonites.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The last Amish congregation in Germany to merge was the Ixheim Amish congregation, which merged with the neighboring Mennonite Church in 1937.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Some Mennonite congregations, including most in Alsace, are descended directly from former Amish congregations.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Although splits happened among the Old Order in the 19th century in Mifflin County, Pennsylvania, a major split occurred in World War I.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] At that time, two very conservative affiliations emerged – the Swartzentruber Amish in Holmes County, Ohio, and the Buchanan Amish in Iowa.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Buchanan Amish soon were joined by like-minded congregations all over the country.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] With Germany's aggression toward the US in World War I came the suppression of the German language in the US that eventually led to language shift of most Pennsylvania German speakers, leaving the Amish and other Old Orders as almost the only speakers by the end of the 20th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] This created a language barrier around the Amish that did not exist before in that form.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the late 1920s, the more change-minded faction of the Old Order Amish, that wanted to adopt the car, broke away from the mainstream and organized under the name Beachy Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] During the Second World War, the old question of military service for the Amish came up again.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because Amish young men in general refused military service, they ended up in the Civilian Public Service (CPS), where they worked mainly in forestry and hospitals.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The fact that many young men worked in hospitals, where they had a lot of contact with more progressive Mennonites and the outside world, had the result that many of these men never joined the Amish church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the 1950s, the Beachy Amish laid heavy emphasis on the New Birth, personal holiness and Sunday School education.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The ones who wanted to preserve the old way of the Beachy became the Old Beachy Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 1966, the New Order Amish were formed after certain congregations left the Old Order Amish due to issues regarding salvation and "the use of modern agricultural methods".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish believe that they have a "hope for salvation", reckoning that "joining with other church members to live according to the Ordnung and the Bible will give them the strength to lives worthy of salvation".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The New Order Amish, on the other hand, affirm that a believer can have assurance—"that one can know the state of his soul while on earth".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Until about 1950, almost all Amish children attended small, rural, non-Amish schools, but then school consolidation and mandatory schooling beyond eighth grade caused Amish opposition.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish communities opened their own Amish schools.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 1972, the United States Supreme Court exempted Amish pupils from compulsory education past eighth grade.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] By the end of the 20th century, almost all Amish children attended Amish schools.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the last quarter of the 20th century, a growing number of Amish men left farm work and started small businesses because of increasing pressure on small-scale farming.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Though a wide variety of small businesses exists among the Amish, construction work and woodworking are quite widespread.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In many Amish settlements, especially the larger ones, farmers are now a minority.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Approximately 12,000 of the 40,000 dairy farms in the United States are Amish-owned as of 2018.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Until the early 20th century, Old Order Amish identity was not linked to the limited use of technologies, as the Old Order Amish and their rural neighbors used the same farm and household technologies.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Questions about the use of technologies also did not play a role in the Old Order division of the second half of the 19th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Telephones were the first important technology that was rejected, soon followed by the rejection of cars, tractors, radios, and many other technological inventions of the 20th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Old Order Mennonites, Old Colony Mennonites and the Amish are often grouped together in North America's popular press.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Two key concepts for understanding Amish practices are their rejection of *Hochmut* (pride, arrogance, haughtiness) and the high value they place on *Demut* (humility) and *Gelassenheit* (calmness, composure, placidity), often translated as "submission" or "letting be".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] *Gelassenheit* is perhaps better understood as a reluctance to be forward, to be self-promoting, or to assert oneself.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish's willingness to submit to the "Will of Jesus", expressed through group norms, is at odds with the individualism so central to the wider American culture.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish anti-individualist orientation is the motive for rejecting labor-saving technologies that might make one less dependent on the community.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Modern innovations such as electricity might spark a competition for status goods, or photographs might cultivate personal vanity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Electric power lines would be going against the Bible, which says that you shall not be "conformed to the world" (Romans 12:2).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish church membership begins with baptism, usually between the ages of 16 and 23.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] It is a requirement for marriage within the Amish church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Once a person is baptized within the church, he or she may marry only within the faith.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Church districts have between 20 and 40 families and worship services are held every other Sunday in a member's home or barn.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The district is led by a bishop and several ministers and deacons who are chosen by a combination of election and cleromancy (lot).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The rules of the church, the so-called *Ordnung*, which differs to some extent between different districts, is reviewed twice a year by all members of the church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Only if all members give their consent to it, Lord's supper is held.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The *Ordnung* must be observed by every member and covers many aspects of day-to-day living, including prohibitions or limitations on the use of power-line electricity, telephones, and automobiles, as well as regulations on clothing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish value rural life, manual labor, humility, and *Gelassenheit*, all under the auspices of living what they interpret to be God's word.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Members who do not conform to these community expectations and who cannot be convinced to repent face excommunication and shunning.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The modes of shunning vary between different communities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] On average, about 85 percent of Amish youth choose to be baptized and join the church.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] During an adolescent period of *rumspringa* (lit.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish lifestyle is regulated by the *Ordnung* ("rules"), which differs slightly from community to community and from district to district within a community.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] There is no central Amish governing authority.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Each Amish community makes its own decisions, and what is acceptable in one community may be unacceptable in another.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The *Ordnung* is agreed upon – or changed – within the whole community of baptized members prior to Communion which takes place two times a year.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The meeting where the *Ordnung* is discussed is called *Ordnungsgemeine* in Standard German and *Ordningsgmee* in Pennsylvania Dutch.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The *Ordnung* includes such matters as dress, permissible uses of technology, religious duties, and rules regarding interaction with outsiders.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In these meetings, women also vote in questions concerning the *Ordnung*.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Bearing children, raising them, and socializing with neighbors and relatives are the greatest functions of the Amish family.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish typically believe that large families are a blessing from God.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Farm families tend to be larger, because sons are needed to perform farm labor.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Community is central to the Amish way of life.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Working hard is considered godly, and some technological advancements have been considered undesirable because they reduce the need for hard work.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish also avoid using technologies they believe will disrupt their traditional lives.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Machines, such as automatic floor cleaners in barns, have historically been rejected as this provides young farmhands with too much free time.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish communities are known for traveling by horse and buggy because they feel horse-drawn vehicles promote a slow pace of life.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Many Amish communities do also allow riding in motor vehicles, such as buses and cars.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They also are allowed to travel by train.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In recent years many Amish people have taken to using electric bicycles as they are faster than either walking or harnessing up a horse and buggy.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are known for their plain attire.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Men wear solid colored shirts, broad-brimmed hats, and suits that signify similarity amongst one another.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish men grow beards to symbolize manhood and marital status, as well as to promote humility.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They are forbidden from growing mustaches because mustaches are seen by the Amish as being affiliated with the military, to which they are strongly opposed, due to their pacifist beliefs.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Women have similar guidelines on how to dress, which are also expressed in the *Ordnung*, the Amish version of legislation.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They are to wear calf-length dresses, muted colors along with bonnets and aprons.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Prayer kapps and bonnets are worn by the women because they are a visual representation of their religious beliefs and promote unity through the tradition of every woman wearing one.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The color of the bonnet signifies whether a woman is single or married.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Single women wear black bonnets and married women wear white.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The color coding of bonnets is important because women are not allowed to wear jewelry, such as wedding rings, as it is seen as drawing attention to the body which can induce pride in the individual.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] All clothing is sewn by hand, but the way to fasten the garment widely depends on whether the Amish person is a part of the New Order or Old Order Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish seldom, if ever, use buttons because they are seen as too flashy; instead, they use the hook and eye approach to fashion clothing or metal snaps.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The New Order Amish are slightly more progressive and allow the usage of buttons to help attire clothing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish cuisine is noted for its simplicity and traditional qualities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Food plays an important part in Amish social life and is served at potlucks, weddings, fundraisers, farewells, and other events.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Many Amish foods are sold at markets, including pies, preserves, bread mixes, pickled produce, desserts, and canned goods.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Many Amish communities have also established restaurants for visitors.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish meat consumption is similar to the American average though they tend to eat more preserved meat.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Distinguishing local myths from culinary fact is accomplished by dedicated anthropological field studies in combination with studies of literary sources, usually newspaper archives, diaries, and household records.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Historically, Amish communities were primarily agrarian, with most families engaged in farming.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] However, rapid population growth and the resulting social and economic pressures have led to significant diversification in Amish employment patterns since the mid-20th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In the Greater Holmes County settlement area of Ohio—the largest Amish community—approximately 75% of married males were full-time farmers in 1965.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] By contrast, only about 40% remained so by 1996, indicating a marked shift toward non-farming occupations.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The ratio of farmers to non-farmers in the region declined from 2.41 to 0.61 during this period.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] More recent analyses of the *Holmes County Amish Directory* show that this move away from farming continues.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In a 2015 census-level study, only 16% of male family heads who listed an occupation were farmers, while the remainder worked in other sectors.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Common non-farming occupations include roofing, carpentry, construction, metalworking, and small-scale manufacturing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Despite the shift away from farming in recent decades, Amish communities still regard farming as a key occupation that strengthens household and community ties.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Small farms provide a social foundation for family structures and the socialization of children.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Through these shared agricultural experiences, farming families build a collective identity, reinforcing social, ethnic, and religious bonds.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish and Mennonite communities across many states have turned to dog breeding as a lucrative source of income.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] According to the USDA list of licensees, over 98% of Ohio's puppy mills are run by the Amish, as are 97% of Indiana's, and 63% of Pennsylvania's.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In Lancaster County, Pennsylvania, there are roughly 300 licensed breeders, and an estimated further 600 unlicensed breeding facilities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The controversies surrounding the Amish and the exploitation of animals extend beyond the cruelty of puppy mills.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish draft horses in poor condition appear regularly at auctions to be sold for meat after a hard working life, often lame and emaciated.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Reports of animal abuse are also common.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish fall into three main subgroups—the Old Order Amish, the New Order Amish, and the Amish Mennonites—all of whom wear plain dress and live their life according to the Bible as codified in their church's *Ordnung*.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Over the years, the Amish churches have divided many times mostly over questions concerning the Ordnung, but also over doctrinal disputes, mainly about shunning.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The largest group, the "Old Order" Amish, a conservative faction that separated from other Amish in the 1860s, are those who have most emphasized traditional practices and beliefs.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The New Order Amish are a group of Amish whom some scholars see best described as a subgroup of Old Order Amish, despite the name.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] As of 2011, about 40 different Old Order Amish affiliations were known to exist.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The table below indicates the use of certain technologies by different Amish affiliations.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The use of cars is not allowed by any Old and New Order Amish, nor are radio, television, or in most cases the use of the Internet.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Three affiliations—"Lancaster", "Holmes Old Order" and "Elkhart-LaGrange"—are not only the three largest affiliations but also represent the mainstream among the Old Order Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The most conservative affiliations are at the top, the most modern ones at the bottom.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Technologies used by very few are on the left; the ones used by most are on the right.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The percentage of all Amish who use a technology is also indicated approximately.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish culture involves lower greenhouse gas emissions in all sectors and activities with the exception of diet, and their per-person emissions has been estimated to be less than one quarter that of the wider society.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most Old Order Amish, all New Order Amish, all Old Beachy Amish and most Kauffman Amish Mennonites speak Pennsylvania Dutch, and refer to non-Amish people as "English", regardless of ethnicity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Two Old Order Amish subgroups – called Swiss Amish – whose ancestors migrated to the United States in the 1850s speak a form of Bernese German (Adams County, Indiana, and daughter settlements) or a Low Alemannic Alsatian dialect (Allen County, IN and daughter settlements).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the word "Dutch" in "Pennsylvania Dutch" is not a mistranslation, but rather a corruption of the Pennsylvania German endonym *Deitsch*, which means "Pennsylvania Dutch / German" or "German".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Ultimately, the terms Deitsch, Dutch, Diets and Deutsch are all cognates and descend from the Proto-Germanic word **þiudiskaz* meaning "popular" or "of the people".
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] According to one scholar, "today, almost all Amish are functionally bilingual in Pennsylvania Dutch and English; however, domains of usage are sharply separated.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Pennsylvania Dutch dominates in most in-group settings, such as the dinner table and preaching in church services.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In contrast, English is used for most reading and writing.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] English is also the medium of instruction in schools and is used in business transactions and often, out of politeness, in situations involving interactions with non-Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Finally, the Amish read prayers and sing in Standard German (which, in Pennsylvania Dutch, is called *Hochdeitsch*) at church services.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The distinctive use of three different languages serves as a powerful conveyor of Amish identity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish largely share a German or Swiss-German ancestry.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They generally use the term "Amish" only for members of their faith community and not as an ethnic designation.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] However some Amish descendants recognize their cultural background knowing that their genetic and cultural traits are uniquely different from other ethnicities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Those who choose to affiliate with the church, or young children raised in Amish homes, but too young to yet be church members, are considered to be Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Certain Mennonite churches have a high number of people who were formerly from Amish congregations.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Although more Amish immigrated to North America in the 19th century than during the 18th century, most of today's Amish descend from 18th-century immigrants.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The latter tended to emphasize tradition to a greater extent, and were perhaps more likely to maintain a separate Amish identity.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] There are a number of Amish Mennonite church groups that had never in their history been associated with the Old Order Amish because they split from the Amish mainstream in the time when the Old Orders formed in the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The former Western Ontario Mennonite Conference (WOMC) was made up almost entirely of former Amish Mennonites who reunited with the Mennonite Church in Canada.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Orland Gingerich's book *The Amish of Canada* devotes the vast majority of its pages not to the Beachy or Old Order Amish, but to congregations in the former WOMC.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Several other groups, called "para-Amish" by G.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Waldrep and others, share many characteristics with the Amish, such as horse-and-buggy transportation, plain dress, and the preservation of the German language.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The members of these groups are largely of Amish origin, but they are not in fellowship with other Amish groups because they adhere to theological doctrines (e.g., assurance of salvation) or practices (community of goods) that are normally not accepted among mainstream Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Bergholz Community is a different case; it is not seen as Amish anymore because the community has shifted away from many core Amish principles.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because the Amish are usually baptized no earlier than 18 and children are not counted in local congregation numbers, estimating their numbers is difficult.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Thus, from 1992 to 2008, population growth among the Amish in North America was 84 percent (3.6 percent per year).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] During that time, they established 184 new settlements and moved into six new states.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2000, about 165,620 Old Order Amish resided in the United States, of whom 73,609 were church members.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are among the fastest-growing populations in the world, with an average of seven children per family in the 1970s and a total fertility rate of 5.3 in the 2010s.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Due to this, their population doubles in size roughly every 20 years.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2010, a few religious bodies, including the Amish, changed the way their adherents were reported to better match the standards of the Association of Statisticians of American Religious Bodies.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] When looking at all Amish adherents and not solely Old Order Amish, about 241,000 Amish adherents were in 28 U.S. states in 2010.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish added 100,000 more adherents in just 9 years, reaching 411,000 in 2025 in comparison with the 308,000 figure from 2016, at the same time the total number of settlements grew from 509 to 684 (+34%), and the number of districts went from 2,259 to 3,114 (+38%).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The United States is the home to the overwhelming majority (over 98 percent) of Amish people.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2025, Old Order communities were present in 32 U.S. states.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The total Amish population in the United States as of June 2025 has stood at 404,575 up 9,855 or 2.5 percent, compared to the previous year.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Pennsylvania has the largest population (95.4 thousand), followed by Ohio (86.3 thousand) and Indiana (67.3 thousand), as of June 2025.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The largest Amish settlements are in Lancaster County in southeastern Pennsylvania (44.7 thousand), Holmes County and adjacent counties in northeastern Ohio (39.0 thousand), and Elkhart and LaGrange counties in northeastern Indiana (29.9 thousand), as of June 2025.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The highest concentration of Amish in the world is in the Holmes County community; nearly 50 percent of the entire population of Holmes County is Amish as of 2010.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The largest concentration of Amish west of the Mississippi River is in Missouri, with other settlements in eastern Iowa and southeast Minnesota.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The largest Amish settlements in Iowa are located near Kalona and Bloomfield.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The largest settlement in Wisconsin is near Cashton with 13 congregations, i.e. about 2,000 people in 2009.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Because of the rapid population growth of the Amish communities, new settlements in the United States are being established each year, thus: 18 new settlements were established in 2016, 22 in 2017, 17 in 2018, 26 in 2019, 26 in 2020, 18 in 2021, 19 in 2022, 39 in 2023 and 19 in 2024.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The adjacent table shows the eight states with the largest Amish population in the years 1992, 2000, 2010, 2020 and 2025.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The **Amish of Canada** settled in southwestern Ontario, having come from the United States in 1815 and directly from Europe in 1822.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They numbered about 1,000 people in 1991.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Today, the Canadian Amish population exceeds 6,000 people, living in 20 different communities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Rising land prices are causing some Amish families to leave Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Since 2017, some Amish families originally from Ontario have settled in Manitoba's Rural Municipality of Stuartburn.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish in Canada trace their origins to two distinct waves of Amish Mennonite migration.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The first wave occurred in the 1880s, when a group of Amish Mennonites from Europe settled in Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The second wave of Old Order Amish migration occurred in the 1950s, when Amish communities from states such as Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Iowa established settlements in Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The majority of Old Order settlements are located in the province of Ontario, namely Oxford (Norwich Township) and Norfolk Counties.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] A small community is also established in Bruce County (Huron-Kinloss Township) near Lucknow.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2016, several dozen Old Order Amish families founded two new settlements in Kings County in the province of Prince Edward Island.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Increasing land prices in Ontario had reportedly limited the ability of members in those communities to purchase new farms.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] At about the same time a new settlement was founded near Perth-Andover in New Brunswick, only about 12 km (7.5 mi) from Amish settlements in Maine.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2017, an Amish settlement was founded in Manitoba near Stuartburn.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2024 this colony ceased to exist, as the Amish have sold their properties and moved to Minnesota.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] There is only one colony left in Latin America, in Bolivia.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Argentina colony ceased to exist as of 2024.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The first attempt by Old Order Amish to settle in Latin America was in Paradise Valley, near Galeana, Nuevo León, Mexico, but the settlement lasted from only 1923 to 1929.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] An Amish settlement was tried in Honduras from about 1968 to 1978, but this settlement failed too.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In 2015, new settlements of New Order Amish were founded east of Catamarca, Argentina, and Colonia Naranjita, Bolivia, about 75 miles (121 km) southwest of Santa Cruz.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most of the members of these new communities come from Old Colony Mennonite background and have been living in the area for several decades.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In Europe, no split occurred between Old Order Amish and Amish Mennonites; like the Amish Mennonites in North America, the European Amish assimilated into the Mennonite mainstream during the second half of the 19th century through the first decades of the 20th century.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Eventually, they dropped the word "Amish" from the names of their congregations and lost their Amish identity and culture.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The last European Amish congregation joined the Mennonites in 1937 in Ixheim, today part of Zweibrücken in the Palatinate region.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Only a few hundred outsiders, so-called seekers, have ever joined the Old Order Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Since 1950, only some 75 non-Anabaptist people have joined and remained lifelong members of the Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Since 1990, some twenty people of Russian Mennonite background have joined the Amish in Aylmer, Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The "Michigan Amish Churches", with which Smyrna and Manton affiliated, are said to be more open to seekers and converts than other Amish churches.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Most of the members of these two para-Amish communities originally came from plain churches, i.e., Old Order Amish, Old Order Mennonite, or Old German Baptist Brethren.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] More people have tested Old Order Amish life for weeks, months, or even years, but in the end decided not to join.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Others remain close to the Amish, but never think of joining.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] On the other hand, the Beachy Amish, many of whom conduct their services in English and allow for a limited range of modern conveniences, regularly receive seekers into their churches as visitors, and eventually, as members.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Various congregations belonging to Old Order Anabaptism and Conservative Anabaptism lend support to Christian Aid Ministries, a missionary arm of these movements, along with Iron Curtain and Freiheit Messengers Prison Ministry.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish populations have higher incidences of particular conditions, including dwarfism, Angelman syndrome, and various metabolic disorders, as well as an unusual distribution of blood types.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish represent a collection of different demes or genetically closed communities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Although the Amish do not have higher incidence of genetic disorders than the general population, since almost all Amish descend from a few hundred 18th-century founders, some recessive conditions are more prevalent (an example of the founder effect).
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Some of these disorders are rare or unique, and are serious enough to increase the mortality rate among Amish children.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are aware of the advantages of exogamy, but for religious reasons, marry only within their communities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The majority of Amish accept these as *Gottes Wille* (God's will); they reject the use of preventive genetic tests prior to marriage and genetic testing of unborn children to discover genetic disorders.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] When children are born with a disorder, they are accepted into the community and tasked with chores within their ability.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] However, Amish are willing to participate in studies of genetic diseases.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Their extensive family histories are useful to researchers investigating diseases such as Alzheimer's, Parkinson's, and macular degeneration.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] While the Amish are at an increased risk for some genetic disorders, researchers have found their tendency for clean living can lead to better health.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Overall cancer rates in the Amish are reduced and tobacco-related cancers in Amish adults are 37 percent and non-tobacco-related cancers are 72 percent of the rate for Ohio adults.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Skin cancer rates are lower for Amish, even though many Amish make their living working outdoors where they are exposed to sunlight.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] They are typically covered and dressed by wearing wide-brimmed hats and long sleeves which protect their skin.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Treating genetic problems is the mission of Clinic for Special Children in Strasburg, Pennsylvania, which has developed effective treatments for such problems as maple syrup urine disease, which once was fatal.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The clinic is embraced by most Amish, ending the need for parents to leave the community to receive proper care for their children, an action that might result in shunning.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Another clinic is DDC Clinic for Special Needs Children, located in Middlefield, Ohio, for special-needs children with inherited or metabolic disorders.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The DDC Clinic provides treatment, research, and educational services to Amish and non-Amish children and their families.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] People's Helpers is an Amish-organized network of mental health caregivers who help families dealing with mental illness and recommend professional counselors.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Suicide rates for the Amish are about half that of the general population.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Old Order Amish do not typically carry private commercial health insurance.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] A handful of American hospitals, starting in the mid-1990s, created special outreach programs to assist the Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] In some Amish communities, the church will collect money from its members to help pay for medical bills of other members.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Although the Amish are often perceived by outsiders as rejecting all modern technologies, this is not the case and modern medicine is employed by Amish communities, including hospital births and other advanced treatments.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] As they go without health insurance and pay up front for services, Amish individuals will often travel to Mexico for non-urgent care and surgery to reduce costs.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Amish typically have a large number of children, not because of any lack of birth control but because of their beliefs and because large families are useful in agrarian communities.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] Some communities openly allow access to birth control to women whose health would be compromised by childbirth.
[src:crokinole/amish-p01] The Amish are against abortion and also find "artificial insemination, genetics, eugenics, and stem cell research" to be "inconsistent with Amish values and beliefs".
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] As time has passed, the Amish have felt pressures from the modern world.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Issues such as taxation, education, law and its enforcement, and occasional discrimination and hostility are areas of difficulty.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The modern way of life in general has increasingly diverged from that of Amish society.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] On occasion, this has resulted in sporadic discrimination and hostility from their neighbors, such as throwing of stones or other objects at Amish horse-drawn carriages on the roads.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The Amish do not usually educate their children past the eighth grade, believing that the basic knowledge offered up to that point is sufficient to prepare one for the Amish lifestyle.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Almost no Amish go to high school and college.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] In many communities, the Amish operate their own schools, which are typically one-room schoolhouses with teachers (usually young, unmarried women) from the Amish community.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] On May 19, 1972, Jonas Yoder and Wallace Miller of the Old Order Amish, and Adin Yutzy of the Conservative Amish Mennonite Church were each fined $5 for refusing to send their children, aged 14 and 15, to high school.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Yoder* (1972), the Wisconsin Supreme Court overturned the conviction, and the U.S.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Supreme Court affirmed this, finding the benefits of universal education were not sufficient justification to overcome scrutiny under the Free Exercise Clause of the First Amendment.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The Amish are subject to sales and property taxes.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] As they seldom own motor vehicles, they rarely have occasion to pay motor vehicle registration fees or spend money on the purchase of fuel for vehicles.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Under their beliefs and traditions, generally the Amish do not agree with the idea of Social Security benefits and have a religious objection to insurance.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] On this basis, the United States Internal Revenue Service agreed in 1961 that they did not need to pay Social Security-related taxes.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] In 1965, this policy was codified into law.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Self-employed individuals in certain sects do not pay into or receive benefits from the United States Social Security system.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] This exemption applies to a religious group that is conscientiously opposed to accepting benefits of any private or public insurance, provides a reasonable level of living for its dependent members, and has existed continuously since December 31, 1950.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Supreme Court clarified in 1982 that Amish employers are not exempt, but only those Amish individuals who are self-employed.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] In 1964, Pathway Publishers was founded by two Amish farmers to print more material about the Amish and Anabaptists in general.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] It is located in LaGrange, Indiana, and Aylmer, Ontario.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Pathway has become the major publisher of Amish school textbooks, general-reading books, and periodicals.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Also, a number of private enterprises publish everything from general reading to reprints of older literature that has been considered of great value to Amish families.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Some Amish read the Pennsylvania German newspaper *Hiwwe wie Driwwe*, and some of them even contribute dialect texts.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Anabaptist groups that sprang from the same late 19th-century Old Order Movement as the Amish share their Pennsylvania German heritage and often still retain similar features in dress.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] These Old Order groups include different subgroups of Old Order Mennonites, traditional Schwarzenau Brethren and Old Order River Brethren.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The Noah Hoover Old Order Mennonites are so similar in outward aspects to the Old Order Amish, including dress, beards, horse and buggy, extreme restrictions on modern technology, Pennsylvania German language, that they are often perceived as Amish and even called Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Conservative "Russian" Mennonites and Hutterites who also dress plain and speak German dialects emigrated from other European regions at different times with different German dialects, separate cultures, and related but different religious traditions.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Particularly, the Hutterites live communally and are generally accepting of modern technology.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] In western Ukraine, the *Kashketnyky* have been compared to the Amish, due to their similar beliefs of plain living and pacifism.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The few remaining Plain Quakers are similar in manner and lifestyle, including their attitudes toward war, but are unrelated to the Amish.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Early Quakers were influenced, to some degree, by the Anabaptists, and in turn influenced the Amish in colonial Pennsylvania.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Almost all modern Quakers have since abandoned their traditional dress.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The Northkill Amish Settlement, established in 1740 in Berks County, Pennsylvania, was the first identifiable Amish community in the New World.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] During the French and Indian War, the Hochstetler Massacre occurred: Local tribes attacked the Jacob Hochstetler homestead in the Northkill settlement on September 19, 1757.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The sons of the family took their weapons but father Jacob did not allow them to shoot due to the Anabaptist doctrine of nonresistance.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Jacob Sr.'s wife, Anna (Lorentz) Hochstetler, a daughter (name unknown) and Jacob Jr. were killed by the Native Americans.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Jacob Sr. and sons Joseph and Christian were taken captive.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] Jacob escaped after about eight months, but the boys were held for several years.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] When freed, both of these sons joined the church and one of them became a minister.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] As early as 1809 Amish were farming side by side with Native American farmers in Pennsylvania.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] According to Cones Kupwah Snowflower, a Shawnee genealogist, the Amish and Quakers were known to incorporate Native Americans into their families to protect them from ill-treatment, especially after the Removal Act of 1832.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The Amish, as pacifists, did not engage in warfare with Native Americans, nor displace them directly, but were among the European immigrants whose arrival resulted in their displacement.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] In 2012, the Lancaster Mennonite Historical Society collaborated with the Native American community to construct a replica Iroquois Longhouse.
[src:crokinole/amish-p02] The following years saw continuous efforts to meet with local Indigenous in a series of reconciliation meetings, a process started by Lancaster Mennonites more than a decade prior.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] In printing, **anti-set-off spray powder** is used to make an air gap between printed sheets of paper.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] This enables the ink to dry naturally and therefore avoid the unwanted transfer of ink from one printed sheet to another.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] The problem can occur with most types of printing.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Anti-set-off spray powder is generally made from natural starches from plants and vegetables.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] There remains a demand for soluble powders (sometimes known as vanished powders) based on natural sugars which are often used when the final printed sheet is to be varnished.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] In addition there is still a relatively small amount of powder made from minerals (e.g.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Calcium Carbonate, rather than Talc) used in offset litho printing; however these mineral powders are not so popular because of the potential health implications and abrasive properties.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Spray powder is used to separate printed sheets to enable air to naturally dry the printing ink.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] The diameter of the powder used is relative to the density (g/m2) of the stock (paper or board) being printed.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] For 150 g/m2 paper the ideal anti-set-off spray powder would be 15 μm in diameter, for 200 g/m2 20 μm, through to 70 μm for heavy board (700 g/m2).
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Most manufactures of spray powder offer both coated and uncoated powders.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Uncoated powders are generally less expensive and are based on natural food-grade starches typically derived from corn (maize), wheat, semolina, potato, tapioca and rice depending on the diameter required.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Coated powders use the same range of raw materials but are encapsulated with a minuscule amount of natural coatings which enable the powders to flow freely though the spray guns on sheet-fed offset-litho printing presses.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Enhanced versions of these coatings are used to give specific electrostatic (anti-static) and hydrophobic properties.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Spray powder is not used on rotary presses including rotary letterpress, web offset (often used for printing magazines), flexographic (often used for printing flexible packaging and labels) or gravure (often used for printing long-run catalogues).
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Similarly, spray powder is not generally used in sheet-fed (silk) screen-printing, ink-jet or toner based digital printing.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] In the UK, many Carrom players use a version of anti-set-off spray powder from the printing industry which has specific electrostatic properties with particles of 50 micrometres in diameter.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] As health and safety has become more important to the environment and to the work forces, a small number of anti-set-off spray powder manufacturers had introduced highly clarified powders by 2007, in advance of EU legislation.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] This new generation of powders have typically less than 3% of particles of less than 10 μm and almost no particles below 5 μm which are generally regarded in the industry as dust.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] To put this in context typical human hair is 20 – 40 μm.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] The printing industry regards anti-set-off spray powder as a necessary evil.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] Ideally printers would prefer not to use it, but it remains the only practical way to ensure a stack of printed paper at the end of a printing press does not set-off.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] In recent years there has been an emergence of printing presses which use inks that are cured (dried) with powerful UV lamps.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] As each sheet is individually dried there is no need for spray powder.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] However, as these machines require specialty inks which are much more expensive than conventional inks, and the UV lamps use a significant amount of energy, the vast majority of new sheet-fed presses sold in 2007 still used anti-set-off spray powder.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] In addition to its use in the printing and packaging industry, spray powder is also used in the manufacture of float glass to enable the large sheets to slide easily over each other.
[src:crokinole/anti-set-off-spray-powder] It is also used in the manufacture of plastic food wrap and similar products to help prevent pieces of plastic from sticking together because of static electricity.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP **Aquabike World Championship** is a powerboating sports competition.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is the premier class of jetski racing, founded in 1992.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Aquabike jetskis are personal watercraft vehicles purpose-built for racing and modified according to class.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship is organized and promoted by H2O Racing Ltd on behalf of the Union Internationale Motonautique (UIM), the governing body of powerboating and the exclusive entity recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] This term refers to an Aquabike designed to be stood upon and is powered by rear jet propulsion with a completely closed system.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Skis, by definition, are the most demanding to ride as they require high fitness levels and great physical strength as well as agility in the legs and arms.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] According to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork, this type of Aquabike is used for three different categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Another category (GP3) also exists in which younger drivers, between the ages of 11 and 14, compete.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are also used in the Freestyle category however this requires further structural changes to the size and motor, allowing the Ski to become considerably shorter in length, lighter in weight and able to perform better at low engine speeds.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Ski bikes are currently used in three different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Parallel Slalom and Freestyle.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout refers to the largest and most powerful bikes in the Championship.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are designed for driving while seated and feature a saddle (located towards the front) and a rear jet or a completely closed propulsion system.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Runabouts are the most common jetski in the world, as they can also be used for recreational purposes.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] As with Ski bikes, Runabout bikes are used for three different racing categories: GP1, GP2 and Stock, according to the different degrees of modifications to the engine and bodywork.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in five different disciplines of the UIM-ABP Aquabike World Championship: Closed Circuit, Offshore, Endurance, Jet Raid and Parallel Slalom.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Regulations require that the path does not exceed 1300m in length.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is marked out by different coloured buoys: yellow (right turn) and red (left turn).
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to complete a set number of laps (varies according to racing division) at the end of which, the chequered flag is waved by marshals.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] These races are held across long distances and require serious consideration to be taken for refuelling as this is usually done on land.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The circuit is bordered by large buoys (visible from long distances) or by natural landmarks like coastline, lighthouses, islands, rocks, etc .
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Endurance races are held on long closed circuits.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] As endurance races are testing the long-term resistance of a rider and their bike, these races tend to last several hours and are more akin to a marathon as opposed to a sprint.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Given the long duration of the race, supplies are required in advance to ensure everything runs smoothly.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Runabout bikes are used in endurance races.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] These races are spread over several stages.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are required to travel long distances marked by checkpoints to complete the race.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] These races are often very time consuming as riders cover one expanse of water, and reach the coast on the other side, where their bike then has to be transported by land to the next race stage.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] This category is more of a competition than a race.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Riders are given a duration of three minutes to perform a rehearsed routine, one at a time.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The stunts are evaluated by a team of five expert judges.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The evaluation criteria are: quality, quantity and variety.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The most common moves are Backflip, Barrel Roll, 360, Superman and Submarine.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Safety and security is of paramount importance during all the races and tests.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] Each member of the rescue team present at all races is required to have a certificate proving their ability to rescue and transport personal watercraft and injured riders.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] The support of the firefighters and patrol boats is essential as they ensure the immediate action in case of more serious accidents.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] On the ground, there is a medical team specialised in traumatology who are able to accompany the riders to the closest hospital to the race site.
[src:crokinole/aquabike-world-championship] In offshore racing, there is also a helicopter rescue service.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] The **Archery World Cup** is a competition **outdoor**organized by World Archery, where the archers compete in four stages in four countries and the best eight archers of each category (from 2010, four archers during 2006–09) advance to an additional stage to contest the Archery World Cup Final.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] It has received plaudits for its innovative approach to the sport, raising its profile and reach.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] From 2013, the World Cup is broadcast live on Eurosport.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] It carries sponsorship from Kia and Longines, which supports the annual Longines Prize of Precision for archery, for the "best male and female athletes that master bow and arrow through concentration, balance, accuracy, and skill".
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] The following venues have hosted stages of the World Cup Final.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] The Longines Prize for Precision is awarded to the male and female archers who shoot the most 10s over the course of the competition at the end of the season.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] It has been awarded since 2010 and is awarded to compound and recurve archers in alternate years.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] Winners receive a trophy, watch and cash prize of 5,000 CHF.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of all medals (including stage and finals).
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] The following table shows the total number of individual medals (including stage and finals).
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] An **Indoor Archery World Cup** was inaugurated in 2010.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] It is played in the off-season (November to February), with fewer stages and the final competed in Las Vegas.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] In 2014, the stages were held in Marrakesh, Singapore and Telford.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] 2019-2020 Indoor Archery World Series have 6 qualification and one final stage.
[src:crokinole/archery-world-cup] After 2018, the World Indoor Archery Championships were discontinued, leaving the Indoor Archery World Series as the premier championship in indoor archery.
[src:crokinole/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The **Artistic Billiards World Championship** is a carom billiards tournament in the discipline of artistic billiards, organized by the Confédération International de Billard Artistique.
[src:crokinole/artistic-billiards-world-championship] Raymond Steylaerts of Belgium won the tournament six times, more than any other player.
[src:crokinole/artistic-billiards-world-championship] The winners have mainly been European, and more commonly Belgian.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Board dimensions vary with a playing surface typically of polished wood or laminate approximately 26 inches (660 mm) in diameter.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The arrangement is 3 concentric rings worth 5, 10, and 15 points as you move in from the outside.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] There is a shallow 20-point hole at the centre.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The inner 15-point ring is guarded with 8 small bumpers or posts.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The outer ring of the board is divided into four quadrants.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The outer edge of the board is raised slightly to keep errant shots from flying out, with a gutter between the playing surface and the edge to collect discarded pieces.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Crokinole boards are typically octagonal or round in shape.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The wooden discs are roughly checker-sized, slightly smaller in diameter than the board's central hole, and typically have one side slightly concave and one side slightly convex, mainly due to the inherent features of wood, more than a planned design.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Alternatively, the game may be played with ring-shaped pieces with a central hole.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The discs were sometimes also called biscuits in the past in southwestern Ontario.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The use of any lubricating powder in crokinole is controversial, with some purists reviling the practice.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Powder is sometimes used to ensure pieces slide smoothly on the surface.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Boric acid was popular for a long time, but is now considered toxic and has been replaced with safer substitutes.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The EU has classified Boric acid as a "Serious Health Hazard".
[src:crokinole/crokinole] In the UK, many players use a version of anti-set-off spray powder, from the printing industry, which has specific electrostatic properties, with particles of 50-micrometre diameter (1.97×10−5 in).
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The powder is made of pure food-grade plant/vegetable starch.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The World Crokinole Championships in Tavistock, Ontario, Canada, states: "The WCC waxes boards, as required, with paste wax.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] On tournament day powdered shuffleboard wax (CAPO fast speed, yellow and white container) is placed in the ditch.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Only tournament organizers will apply quality granular shuffleboard wax.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Wax will be placed in the ditch area so that players can rub their discs in the wax prior to shooting, if they desire.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Contestants are not allowed to apply lubricants of any type to the board.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Absolutely no other lubricant will be allowed".
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Crokinole is most commonly played by two players, or by four players in teams of two, with partners sitting across the board from each other.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Players take turns flicking their discs from the outer edge of their quadrant of the board onto the playfield.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Shooting is usually done by flicking the disc with a finger, though sometimes small cue sticks may be used.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] If there are any enemy discs on the board, a player must make contact, directly or indirectly, with an enemy disc during the shot.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] If unsuccessful, the shot disc is "fouled" and removed from the board, along with any of the player's other discs that were moved during the shot.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The international association of crokinole (founded in 2009) has laid out rules for tournaments and competition play, but being a grass roots game, there are equally valid variations which can make game play more or less interesting depending on time and context.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] This is often called the "no hiding" rule, since it prevents players from placing their first shots where their opponent must traverse completely through the guarded centre ring to hit them and avoid fouling.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] When playing without this rule, a player may generally make any shot desired, and as long as a disc remains completely inside the outer line of the playfield, it remains on the board.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] During any shot, any disc that falls completely into the recessed central "20" hole (a.k.a. the "Toad" or "Dukie") is removed from play, and counts as twenty points for the owner of the disc at the end of the round, assuming the shot is valid.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Scoring occurs after all pieces (generally 12 per player or team) have been played, and is differential: i.e., the player or team with higher score is awarded the difference between the higher and lower scores for the round, thus only one team or player each round gains points.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Play continues until a predetermined winning score is reached.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The earliest Canadian reference is 1867 (*Sports and Games in Canadian Life: 1700 to the Present* by Howell and Howell, Toronto, MacMillan Company of Canada, 1969, p.61), and the oldest piece dated at 1875 by Ekhardt Wettlaufer.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The earliest known crokinole board was made by craftsman Eckhardt Wettlaufer in 1876 in Perth County, Ontario, Canada.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] It is said Wettlaufer crafted the board as a fifth birthday present for his son Adam, which is now part of the collection at the Joseph Schneider Haus, a national historic site in Kitchener, Ontario, with a focus on Germanic folk art.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Several other home-made boards dating from southwestern Ontario in the 1870s have been discovered since the 1990s.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] A board game similar to crokinole was patented on 20 April 1880 by Joshua K.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Crokinole is often believed to be of Mennonite or Amish origins, but there is no factual data to support such a claim.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The reason for this misconception may be due to its popularity in Mennonite and Amish groups.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The game was viewed as a rather innocuous pastime – unlike the perception that diversions such as card playing or dancing were considered "works of the Devil" as held by many 19th-century Protestant groups.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The oldest roots of crokinole, from the 1860s, suggest the British and South Asian games, such as carrom, are the most likely antecedents of what became crokinole.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] In 2006, a documentary film called *Crokinole* was released.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The world premiere occurred at the Princess Cinema in Waterloo, Ontario, in early 2006.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The movie follows some of the competitors of the 2004 World Crokinole Championship as they prepare for the event.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] 2. in French Canada, a pastry somewhat similar to a doughnut (except for the shape).
[src:crokinole/crokinole] It also used to designate the action of flicking with the finger (Molière, *Le malade imaginaire*; or Voltaire, *Lettre à Frédéric II Roi de Prusse*; etc.), and this seems the most likely origin of the name of the game.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] *Croquignole* was also a synonym of *pichenotte*, a word that gave its name to the different but related games of pichenotte and pitchnut.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] From The Crokinole Book 3rd Edition by Wayne S.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Kelly "Is it possible that the English word 'crokinole' is simply an etymological offspring of the French word 'croquignole'?
[src:crokinole/crokinole] It would appear so for the following reasons.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Going back to the entry for Crokinole in Webster's Third New International Dictionary, within the etymological brackets, it says: [French croquignole, fillip].
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The word fillip, according to Webster's, has two definitions: "1. a blow or gesture made by the sudden forcible release of a finger curled up against the thumb; a short sharp blow.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] 2. to strike by holding the nail of a finger curled up against the ball of the thumb and then suddenly releasing it from that position".
[src:crokinole/crokinole] So it seems evident, then, that our game of crokinole derives its name from the verb form (of croquignole) defining the principal action in the game, that of flicking or 'filliping' a playing piece across the board".
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The word Crokinole is generally acknowledged to have been derived from the French Canadian word "Croquignole", a word with several meanings, such as fillip, snap, biscuit, bun and a woman's wavy hairstyle popular at the turn of the century.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The US state of New York shares border crossings with both of the Canadian provinces of Ontario and Quebec, all three of which are popular "hotbeds" of Crokinole playing.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Crokinole is called *knipsbrat* ('flick-board') (and occasionally *knipsdesh* (flick-table)) in the Plautdietsch spoken by Russian Mennonites.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The World Crokinole Championship (WCC) tournament has been held annually since 1999 on the first Saturday of June in Tavistock, Ontario.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Tavistock was chosen as the host city because it was the home of Eckhardt Wettlaufer, the maker of the earliest known board.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The tournament has seen registration from every Canadian province, several American states, Germany, Australia, Spain, the UK, and Japan.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The WCC singles competition begins with a qualifying round in which competitors play 10 matches against randomly assigned opponents.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The qualifying round is played in a large randomly determined competition.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] At the end of the opening round, the top 16 competitors move on to the playoffs.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The top four in the playoffs advance to a final round robin to play each other, and the top two compete in the finals.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The WCC doubles competition begins with a qualifying round of 8 matches against randomly assigned opponents with the top six teams advancing to a playoff round robin to determine the champions.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The WCC has multiple divisions, including a singles finger-shooting category for competitive players (adult singles), novices (recreational), and younger players (intermediate, 11–14 yrs; junior, 6–10 yrs), as well as a division for cue-shooters (cues singles).
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The WCC also awards a prize for the top 20-hole shooter in the qualifying round of competitive singles, recreational singles, cues singles, intermediate singles, and in the junior singles.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The tournament also holds doubles divisions for competitive fingers-shooting (competitive doubles), novices (recreational doubles), younger players (youth doubles, 6–16yrs), and cues-shooting (cues doubles).
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The official board builder of the World Crokinole Championships is Jeremy Tracey.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The National Crokinole Association (NCA) is an association that supports existing, and the development of new, crokinole clubs and tournaments.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] While the majority of NCA events are based in Ontario, Canada, the NCA has held sanctioned events in the Canadian provinces of PEI and BC, as well as in New York State.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The collection of NCA tournaments is referred to as the NCA Tour.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] Each NCA Tour season begins at the Tavistock World Crokinole Championships in June, and concludes at the Ontario Singles Crokinole Championship in May of the following years.
[src:crokinole/crokinole] The results of each tournament award points for each player, as they compete for their season-ending ranking classification.
